<TEXT>
about 200 college students marched through 
this northern new jersey community friday hoping to defuse 
tensions that flared following the fatal shooting of a black 
teenager by a white policeman 
we sympathize with the death of phillip pannell said walter 
fields an official with the bergen county chapter of the naacp 
we dont condone the violence but we do thoroughly understand the 
anger 
pannell 16 of nearby river edge was shot and killed tuesday 
night by teaneck police officer gary spath who was responding to 
an anonymous telephone tip that a teenager had drawn a gun on 
another youth 
in another development the new york times reported in its 
saturday editions that phillips companions said he had been 
handling a bb pistol before officers confronted them 
the newspaper reported that several youths interviewed 
separately said that phillip was fooling around with the bb gun 
when police approached the group 
pannell put the gun in his coat pocket and took off running just 
before police intended to frisk him and the others the youths told 
the newspaper 
it was then that the officer shot killing pannell they said 
police have said they recovered a loaded 22 caliber gun from 
pannell another youth however told the times that another 
youngster carried the bb pistol away 
spath has since been suspended with pay and his partner wayne 
blanco has been temporarily relieved of his duties acting bergen 
county prosecutor john holl said 
a grand jury is scheduled to begin hearing testimony on the case 
on tuesday 
franklin wilks an attorney representing pannells mother 
thelma pannell held a news conference later friday to release 
details of an independent medical examiners report 
wilks said the report corroborates eyewitnesses who said pannell 
had his arms up in the air at the time he was shot in the back 
witnesses said pannell was running away from police when he was 
shot police said a loaded pistol was found on his body 
wilks said he had not seen a report by the bergen county medical 
examiner which found the boy had been killed by a single shot in 
the back 
a peaceful candlelight vigil wednesday night in remembrance of 
the slain youth turned violent as mostly black teenagers roamed 
local streets smashing store windows and overturning cars 
much of the damage remained visible friday plywood had replaced 
what used to be windows in many businesses along teaneck road 
the students who walked through teaneck were members of the 
union of african student organizations which represents 14 
colleges in northern new jersey they included blacks hispanics 
and whites 
the students set out from the teaneck campus of fairleigh 
dickinson university winding through the township and up teaneck 
road to tryon park close to where phillip was killed the event 
did not disrupt traffic and the group had no police escorts 
during the threehour march participants talked with residents 
and merchants fields said 
we tell them were here because were concerned fields 
said whats needed now is healing we need to come together as a 
community 
at tryon park a human chain was formed around the perimeter of 
a basketball court salaam ismial state coordinator of the union 
of african students organization and fields thanked the crowd for 
its support 
we have to some way somehow find a way to live with one 
another ismial said its unfortunate that it took the death 
of a young man to bring us all together 
fields said he has asked teenagers in teaneck to stay indoors 
during the weekend he said he was convinced that tensions were 
still high in the community which has prided itself on being one 
of the first to voluntarily desegregate it schools in the 1960s 
we havent really reached the emotional peak of this incident 
yet he said its going to be an emotional weekend 
</TEXT>
