<TEXT>
the drug situation in the nations capital is 
improving but city officials are not using all the available 
federal money says national drug chief william j bennett 
the situation remains far from acceptable to be sure but at 
the same time some things are moving in the right direction the 
national drug control policy director said at a news conference 
said friday 
i think its fair to say the record is mixed spotty 
incomplete not nearly as good as anyone would like but also not 
so bad as many people might imagine bennett said in assessing 
progress of a yearold federallocal antidrug effort in the 
district of columbia 
bennett said the citys record murder rate in 1989 was a 
bitter disappointment to all concerned but that the overall 
situation was not as negative as some had expected 
im not here to declare failure bennett said by a sober 
assessment of the merits i dont think thats warranted 
in 1989 438 persons were killed in the nations capital and 
police blamed a flourishing drug trade for more than 60 percent of 
the slayings 
bennett said signs of progress include decreases in the number 
of people arrested who test positive for drugs and of hospital 
emergency room patients who mention drug use 
but the drug policy coordinator said more progress might have 
been made if the city had taken better advantage of available 
federal money 
bennett said for example that the city failed to spend 85 
percent of 23 million in funding for special national guard 
anticrime assistance 
in all federal funding to city antidrug efforts has increased 
by 40 percent since last september and now is at a level 
twoandonehalf times the national average bennett said 
we chose dc for this effort because dc was on fire 
bennett said washington remains a federal priority in the war on 
drugs 
