work recently completed much of the structure 
now valence said the rocks are doing exactly what they are 
supposed to be doing 
louisiana loses 30 to 50 square miles of coastline every year 
an acre every 15 minutes or an area the size of rhode island every 
30 years 
nowhere along the coast was the loss more apparent than about 50 
miles south of new orleans at grand isle the states only 
inhabited barrier island a strip of sand that served as 
headquarters for jean lafitte when the buccaneer was the scourge of 
english and spanish shipping almost 200 years ago 
grand isle along with the rest of louisianas coast once was 
replenished annually by sediment washing down the mississippi 
river but man built locks and dams for commerce and lined the 
lower river with levees to protect communities on its banks 
nature continues to send hurricanes against the island but the 
changes prevent silt from replenishing the sand that washes away 
experts said hard structures such as jetties and seawalls were 
selfdefeating that the waves would find the weak spots and wash 
away the sand there they pointed to failures in galveston texas 
around the florida peninsula and up the coast to fire island ny 
