<TEXT>
frances bullfight season opened today with both 
aficionados and critics intensifying lobbying campaigns in advance 
of expected moves to outlaw the increasingly popular spectacle 
the annual number of corridas programs of several 
bullfights has doubled in the past decade to more than 120 total 
attendance last year was 600000 and a national association of 
fans has been formed to defend bullfighting 
animal protection groups in turn have escalated their 
offensive against bullfighting they want first to stop its spread 
and eventually to ban it 
bullfighting was introduced in france in 1853 at the urging of 
empress eugenie the spanishborn wife of napoleon iii almost a 
century later in 1951 the government enshrined bullfighting in a 
law that authorizes its continuation in towns where it qualifies as 
a longstanding local tradition 
that effectively limited corridas to southern cities and towns 
such as nimes and arles where spanish immigrants have helped 
kindle a passion for bullfighting 
attendance at french bullfights stagnated in the 1970s but began 
increasing steadily in the mid1980s attendance in spain the 
worlds bullfighting capital also is rising 
a recent survey taken by the french fans association the 
national association for the defense of laficion indicated 
that the spectators include large numbers of young people many 
with whitecollar jobs 
promoters have succeeded in obtaining more media coverage for 
bullfighting the countrys increasing popular paytv network 
canal plus now shows highlights of bullfights and the trendy 
leftist parisian daily liberation devoted an entire page today to 
the opening of the season 
for rene berlandier president of the fans association the 
main problem facing bullfighting is excessively high ticket prices 
even with the influx of younger bettereducated fans he said 
the average ticket price of nearly 30 is a burden according to 
his groups polls 33 percent of the fans have less than 1700 in 
annual disposable income 
the growing popularity of bullfighting distresses frances 
society for the protection of animals 
they have created a need in an artificial way said the 
societys president jacqueline faucher of the bullfight promoters 
and they shouldnt talk to me about traditions in this area 
its the tradition of the cashregister above all 
she said the society objects to the idea that the agony and 
the death of an animal should become a spectacle 
in the short term we want to ensure that corridas are truly 
limited to towns where they are traditional according to the law 
in the long term we are battling for the prohibition pure and 
simple of this barbarity 
the biggest threat to bullfighting could come from the european 
parliament where deputies seeking to outlaw it may gain broader 
powers as european integration increases after 1992 
thus far french aficionados arent overly worried by the 
spectre of a ban according to the survey taken by berlandiers 
group their biggest worry for now is that the bulls are becoming 
too feeble 
