been secondclass citizens even though they can be making more 
money than some of the law firms partners jordan said the 
rule change though quite severely restrained may make it easier 
to hold on to such people 
lawyers should not reject all outside or even inhouse 
consulting by nonlawyers he says 
for years consulting businesses that specialize in jury 
selection have helped lawyers pick juries for certain kinds of 
cases jordan noted adding that some day these businesses may be 
brought into the law firms 
consulting is not adverse to a legal client he said some 
law firms have hired english professors for clearwriting programs 
i think any thoughtful lawyer realizes that anything you can do to 
make your case more persuasive you should do it even if that 
means hiring a nonlawyer to help 
but the concepts of diversification and nonlawyer partners have 
their outspoken critics 
this whole idea of onestop shopping is highly dangerous 
said l harold levinson a legal ethics professor at the vanderbilt 
university law school in nashville 
inevitably these nonlawyers will exert some influence on 
culture of the law firm and on the culture of the legal 
profession levinson said there is a need to improve but we 
should improve ourselves rather than sharing with others the 
responsibility to improve 
one potential ethical problem he said stems from the common 
law privilege lawyers enjoy against testifying against their 
clients would the same privilege exist for nonlawyers 
levinson also said the seemingly tempting economics of letting 
nonlawyers play larger roles in law firms may backfire 
lawyers untrained in the specialized services offered by the 
nonlawyer partner will have no way of knowing whether the 
nonlawyer partner is rendering highquality service or not he 
said 
however real the potential pitfalls a number of district of 
columbia law firms appear ready even eager to take let 
nonlawyers in as partners 
