<TEXT>
traffic at border crossings returned to 
normal saturday after a moderately strong earthquake shifted the 
walls of a canada customs office shutting it down temporarily 
authorities said 
us customs inspector john nolte said the crossing between 
blaine and douglas british columbia was closed to northbound 
trucks after the quake which registered 51 on the richter scale 
at 1033 pm pdt friday 
the quake was followed by about a dozen aftershocks the 
strongest registering 41 on the richter scale said scientists at 
the university of washington geophysics center 
unloaded trucks were diverted to the peace arch crossing and 
loaded trucks to the crossing between sumas and huntington british 
columbia about 20 miles to the east 
a few trucks were allowed to pass after about 9 am and 
traffic was back to normal by noon without major delays or backups 
nolte said 
geophysicist steve malone said the quake occurred about three 
miles underground and three miles northeast of deming a town about 
10 miles east of bellingham 
walls at the canada customs office in surrey south of 
vancouver were moved about a quarter of an inch said 
superintendent glenn bonnett 
the building was closed overnight but was reopened after a 
structural inspection and operations appeared to be normal by 
midday said us customs agent randy reed 
earthquake monitors at the university said there were reports of 
minor damage in three washington counties including broken glass 
and items jolted from shelves a canopy at the blaine 
bordercrossing also was cracked they said 
county officials said callers who said they felt the quake 
reported no damage was reported other than pictures falling off a 
wall 
